  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">The drag and diffusion coefficients of a hot hadronic medium have been evaluated by using hidden charm mesons as probes. The scattering amplitudes required for the evaluation of these coefficients are calculated using an effective theory and scattering lengths obtained from lattice QCD calculations. It is found that although the magnitude of the transport coefficients are small their temperature variation is strong. The insignificant momentum diffusion of <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>J</mi><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mi>ψ</mi></math> in the hadronic medium keeps their momentum distribution largely unaltered. Therefore, the task of characterization of quark gluon plasma by using the observed suppression of <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>J</mi><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mi>ψ</mi></math> at high momentum will be comparatively easier.</subfield>
